essential nutrients to the host","Compete with the host for nutrients","Cause disease in immunocompetent hosts"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA commensal relationship is characterised by one organism that \u003Cstrong\u003Ebenefits while causing no harm to the host\u003C/strong\u003E. In the human microbiota, commensal organisms obtain nutrients and a place to live without negatively impacting human health.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECause disease in immunocompetent hosts\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes pathogenic organisms, not commensals\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvide essential nutrients to the host\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes a mutualistic relationship where both organisms benefit\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExchange metabolic products with the host\u003C/strong\u003E - This also describes mutualism rather than commensalism\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompete with the host for nutrients\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes a parasitic relationship where the host is harmed\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EExamples of commensal organisms include many species of \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003ECorynebacterium\u003C/em\u003E that live on human skin. While they benefit from this environment, they neither help nor harm the host under normal circumstances.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Commensalism is a type of symbiotic relationship where one organism benefits while the other is unaffected.","The human microbiota contains many commensal organisms that obtain nutrients from the host without causing harm.","Commensal microorganisms can help prevent colonisation by pathogenic species through competitive exclusion."],"referenc